  <section class="faq-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header"><span class="section-tag">Got Questions?</span><h2>FD Calculator — FAQs</h2><p>Common questions about Fixed Deposits.</p></div>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">Is FD interest taxable?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Yes, FD interest is fully taxable as per your income tax slab. Banks deduct TDS at 10% if your annual FD interest exceeds ₹40,000 (₹50,000 for senior citizens). You can submit Form 15G/15H to avoid TDS if your total income is below the taxable limit. The interest must be reported in your ITR regardless of TDS.</div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">What is the penalty for premature FD withdrawal?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Most banks charge a penalty of 0.5-1% on the applicable interest rate for premature withdrawal. For example, if you booked a 3-year FD at 7.25% but withdraw after 1 year, you'd get the 1-year FD rate minus the penalty. Some banks like SBI charge no penalty for FDs below ₹5 lakhs. Tax-saver FDs (5-year) cannot be withdrawn prematurely.</div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">Are FDs safe? What if the bank fails?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">FDs with banks are insured by DICGC (Deposit Insurance and Credit Guarantee Corporation) up to ₹5 lakhs per depositor per bank — covering both principal and interest. For amounts above ₹5 lakhs, choose PSU banks or highly rated private banks. NBFC FDs are not covered by DICGC but offer higher rates to compensate for the additional risk.</div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">What is the best FD tenure for maximum returns?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Currently, most banks offer the best FD rates for 2-3 year tenures (7-7.90%). Very short (under 1 year) and very long (above 5 years) tenures often have lower rates. Compare rates for your preferred tenure before investing. Also consider laddering — splitting your investment across multiple FDs with different maturities for both liquidity and optimal returns.</div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">Should I invest in FD or mutual funds?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">FDs offer guaranteed returns with zero risk, ideal for short-term goals (1-3 years) and emergency funds. Mutual funds offer potentially higher returns (10-15% p.a.) but with market risk, making them better for long-term goals (5+ years). A balanced approach is recommended — use FDs for stability and mutual fund SIPs for wealth creation.</div></div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="page-content" style="padding-top:0;"><div class="container"><div class="page-cta"><div><h3>Get the Best FD Rates</h3><p>Compare Fixed Deposit rates from 30+ banks and invest for guaranteed, risk-free returns.</p></div><a href="/pages/contact" class="btn btn-outline" style="color:#fff;border:2px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.5);padding:14px 32px;font-size:0.95rem;">Compare Now <i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i></a></div></div></section>

</BaseLayout>
